body:
This is a preview of the functional tests stack. I opened this PR to **get some feedback** on how the tests are written and what is the stack that we are using.

The goal of the PR in is to be able to write functional tests that are ensuring our widgets are actually working inside a real browser on a real application.

This is different test level from our unit tests, we are not going to test every behavior of the widget. We only want to check that once everything is plugged together, the main feature of every widget is here.
## Selenium

To start real browsers and do clicks we have only one real solution: **selenium**.

Basically we will run a local selenium when hacking those tests and we will leverage saucelabs on CI to run on multiple browsers.

I use https://github.com/elgalu/docker-selenium to develop my tests: it's awesome. It has everything we need to run tests locally, inside a docker image.
## webdriver.io

I choosed http://webdriver.io to write functionnal tests. I have already participated in the project, it's really well done and maintained. It's the go-to.
## how

So webdriver.io test runner kicks off, we start a web server that will serve a complete search interface with all the widgets. Much like our npm run dev example but separated to avoid changes in the dev example triggering tests failures.

Then we use the webdriver.io API to launch commands.

Here's a sample test of the clearAll widget:

``` js
import expect from 'expect';
import {clearAll, getCurrentRefinements} from '../utils.js';

describe('clearAll', () => {
  it('clears refinements', () => {
    const firstRefinement = '#hierarchical-categories .item:nth-child(2)';
    const secondRefinement = '#brands .item:nth-child(1)';

    return getCurrentRefinements()
      .then(refinements => expect(refinements.length).toBe(0))
      .click(firstRefinement)
      .click(secondRefinement)
      .then(getCurrentRefinements)
      .then(refinements => expect(refinements.length).toBe(2))
      .then(clearAll)
      .then(getCurrentRefinements)
      .then(refinements => expect(refinements.length).toBe(0));
  });
});
```

So here we just check that:
- the initial state is good, there's no refinement
- once we click on two refinements, we find some refinements
- after clicking on clearAll, we check that we have no more refinements

And that's it for a start on the clearAll widget.

As you can see I started developing some utils that will need to be tested also.

Tell me what you think and in the meantime I will continue adding tests.
